data.name: label66.Text
data.value:
Current Best Graph: This page displays a graph that plots the resultsof the target formula and the current best individual to illustrate how close the run is to success.
Average Difference Graph: Thispage displays a graph which plots the average difference between the results of the current best individual and that of the target formula
Tree View: On completion of therun this page displays the tree and equation of the best individual of the run

data.name: label58.Text
data.value: This system allows you to create a custom genetic algorithm,run it and view the results. The "Setup Values" section on the right of the window allows youto customise different variables and select different methods. Explanations for all of the different method options can be found in the relevent Info page section.For an explanation of what each setup value changes hover over the field and a tooltip will appear.

data.name: label35.Text
data.value:
Full: This method grows each branch of the tree to the maximum depth. All trees within the population that are produced using thie method will be the same shape and size.
Grow: This method has the chance of cutting offbranches before they reach the maximum depth to create trees of varying sizes.
Ramped Half and Half: This method generates halfof the population using the Full method and the other half using the Grow method.

data.name: label29.Text
data.value: Initially each the first generation must be generated.The number of individuals created is determined by the "Population Size" value. In the case of this algorithm the individuals that make up the population are binary expressiontrees. A binary expresison tree is a type of binary tree used to represent expressions, an example is shown to the right

data.name: label36.Text
data.value: After the population has been generated, each individal in the population must be evaluated. Evaluation is the process of assigning each individaul a fitess score value. This value is based on how close the individual is to meeting it's given target.

data.name: label38.Text
data.value: In the case of the algorithm used by this system, the fitness score of a program is based on the difference between the results when usingthe chosen target values produced by the chosen target formula and those produced by the binary expression tree of the individual. Thisis visualised on the "Current Best Graph Page" which shows the curve of the target and the curve of the current best individual. The differnce between the two curves is used to determine thefitness score for that individual. The difference is then normalized on a scale of 1-100 and set as the fitness score of the individual to create a more useable set of numbers.

data.name: label47.Text
data.value:
Proportinate Selection: This method randomly selects an individaul form the population but individuals with higher fitness ratings have a higher chance of being selected. The diagram to the right shows the correlation between fitness score and the likelyhood that they will be selected
Tournament: This method selects two parents at random,compares their fitness ratings and selects the one with the better rating to be used for reproduction.

data.name: label44.Text
data.value: Once all individuals have been assigned a fitness score a new generation must be generated. New individuals are created using individauls from the current generation these individauls are refered to as "Parents" These parents are selected randomly but individuals should have a higher chance of being chosen as parents.

data.name: label51.Text
data.value:
Sub-tree Crossover: In this method a point in the tree of the first parent is randomly chosen, then a copy of the subtree below the chosen point is made. Then a random point is chosen in the tree for the second parent and a copy of the entire tree excluding the subtree below the chosen point is made. The copy of the subtree from the first parent is then combined then replaces the removed subtree within the copy of the second parent
Point Crossover: A copy of the first parent is made and a random point is chosen as the crossover point. Then a random node from the other parent is selected and copied. That copied node then replaces the node at the crossover point of the copy of the first parent.

data.name: label48.Text
data.value: One method for creating a new individual for the next generation is called crossover. This method uses two parents chosen via selection. Then a new individual is created using elements from both parents. This way the aspects of the parents that made them successful enough to be selected will hopefully be passed on to the new individual

data.name: label57.Text
data.value: If the crossover rate and mutation rate do not add up to 100% the remainder of the population will be generated via reproduction. This is the process of selecting a random parent and simply making a copy of it and adding it to the new generation without making alterations.

data.name: label56.Text
data.value:
Crossover Mutation: This method of mutation randomly selects one individual to act as the parent. Then a copy of the individual is made and a ranom node within the copy is selected this node is then replaced by a randomly generated subtree
Point Mutation: This method of mutation selects an individual and makes a copy. then a random node is selected from the copy and replaced with a new random node.

data.name: label55.Text
data.value: One method for creating a new individual for the next generation is called mutation. This method uses one parent chosen via selection. Then a new individual is created by randomly altering different aspects of the individual. The inclusion of mutation in a genetic algorithm helps ensure that the gene pool does not stangnate and promotes diversity.
